Missing steps to achieve a good understanding of the technology Challenges

Advanced receivers
RAN Ability to cater/cope with intra-cell and inter-cell interference at the receiver side. Extra signalling from the network in order to help advanced receivers when coping with interference Evolutions from SIC/PIC; intra-subcarrier equalization; inter-symbol interference (ISI) cancellation for Faster-than-Nyquist; intra-cell interference cancellation for non-orthogonal waveforms and nonorthogonal multiple access (NOMA); Inter-Carrier Interference (ICI) and ISI cancellation for CP-free OFDM Increased simplicity at the network side (relaxed coordination and synchronisation) by allowing a controlled amount of interference at the RX side. Extra signalling to be considered at the network side in order to aid advanced receivers in cancelling inter-cell interference Less complex transmission methods (less need of interference coordination/cancellation at the transmitter side) Additional signalling mechanisms to help receivers from the network side More simplified architecture if cell cooperation is less required Additional/different reference symbols and feedback may be needed in order to support better terminal receivers Very immature when considering non-orthogonal waveforms Proprietary advanced receivers are very mature, but terminal classes/requirements don’t honour better receivers Need to agree on the potential of non-orthogonal waveforms and/or multiple access schemes prior to dealing with extra interference
Extra processing power at the RX side; possibly reduced performance

About spectral efficiency/latency trade off:

1. Processing latency at the receiver is seen as insignificant/negligible compared to other sources of latency for most use cases. May become significant for mission critical use cases such as tactile internet. 2. Hardware design with higher processing capabilities can improve latency but will come at a higher cost. 3. Linear type of advanced receivers only adds insignificant delay. For non-linear types (e.g., SIC receivers), processing delay depends on implementation (soft or hard decision, hardware, etc.)

