Interference coordination
RAN To avoid interference via information exchange between schedulers on network side. Inter-Cell Interference Coordination – Rel.8 Coordinated Multi-Points (CoMP) – Rel. 11 & 12

Potential benefits
Impact on the network node (s) (e.g. complexity)
Impact on the architecture Maturity

In addition: definition of coordination messages on standardized intereNB interfaces for multi-vendor deployments, and/or definition of a central coordinating node, and/or introduction of the beams elevation dimension into the coordination parameters. Enhanced reception performance and reduction of the number of dropped calls A better network resource utilisation by using least loaded base station in CoMP process. An increased received power by joint reception from multiple base stations A reduced interference level by utilising constructively the interference rather than destructively. In one hand CoMP needs a very low level of latency in other hand multiple site reception and transmission add significantly to any delays (communication between different sites). The maximum performance is obtained with centralized scheduling of a quite large number of base stations. That increases the backhaul traffic. As different sites may be connected together C-RAN is proposed/may be applied. CoMP has been the focus of many studies by 3GPP for LTEAdvanced as well as the IEEE for their WiMAX, 802.16 standards.

